# Client-Facing Feature Guide
## Event Ticketing Platform — What Users See & How It Works

---

## WHO USES THIS SYSTEM? — 3 Roles

| Role | Who They Are | What They Can Do |
|------|-------------|-----------------|
| **Guest** | Anyone visiting the site without an account | Browse events, view event details, see pricing |
| **User (Attendee)** | Registered and logged-in person | Everything a guest can do + buy tickets, manage bookings, request refunds |
| **Organizer** | Registered user with Organizer status | Everything a user can do + create/manage events, check in attendees at the door |

> There is also an **Admin** role for platform management (user management, oversight), but this is a back-office concern and not part of the user-facing journey.

---

## THE 7 UI PAGES

---

### PAGE 1 — Home / Event Discovery (`/`)
**Who sees it:** Everyone (guest, user, organizer)

This is the landing page — the first thing anyone sees when they visit the platform.

**What's on this page:**
- **Hero Section** — A large banner with a featured/upcoming event, call-to-action button ("Find Tickets")
- **Search Bar** — Search events by keyword (artist name, event title, venue)
- **Filter Panel** — Filter by: Category (Music, Sports, Conference, Theatre), Date range, City/Venue, Price range
- **Event Cards Grid** — A paginated grid of event cards. Each card shows:
  - Event cover image
  - Event title
  - Date and time
  - Venue name and city
  - Starting price ("From $29")
  - Availability badge ("Selling Fast", "Limited", "Sold Out")

**What a user does here:** Browse, search, filter, click an event card to learn more.

---

### PAGE 2 — Event Detail Page (`/events/[id]`)
**Who sees it:** Everyone

This is the full information page for a specific event. It is the most content-rich page.

**What's on this page:**
- **Event Header** — Large cover image, event title, organizer name, event status badge
- **Date, Time & Venue Section** — Full date, start time, venue name, address, map embed
- **Event Description** — Full text description, lineup, agenda, or program
- **Ticket Tier Selection Panel** — This is the most important component:
  - Lists all available ticket tiers (e.g., "General Admission", "VIP", "Early Bird")
  - For each tier: name, price, seats remaining, description
  - Dynamic pricing indicator ("🔥 High demand — price increased 25%") if surge is active
  - Quantity selector (how many tickets to buy)
  - "Add to Cart" / "Reserve Now" button
- **Social Share** — share buttons for spreading the event

**What a user does here:** Read about the event → choose a ticket tier → select quantity → click Reserve.

---

### PAGE 3 — Cart / Reservation Pending (`/cart`)
**Who sees it:** Logged-in users only

After clicking "Reserve Now," the user lands here. This page represents the **5-minute reservation window** — seats are held for this user, but no payment has been taken yet.

**What's on this page:**
- **Countdown Timer** — A live countdown (e.g., "Your seats are held for 4:32 — complete checkout before time expires")
- **Booking Summary Card** — Event name, date, tier selected, quantity, price breakdown
- **Price Breakdown Panel**:
  - Base price
  - Applied discount (Early Bird / Group Discount) if any
  - Surge indicator if dynamic pricing is active
  - Total amount
- **Proceed to Checkout Button** — Takes the user to Stripe payment
- **Cancel / Release Seats Button** — Releases the hold if the user changes their mind

**The urgency:** If the user walks away without paying and the 5-minute timer hits zero, the system automatically releases the held seats back to inventory. The cart empties and the user must start over.

**What a user does here:** Review their selection → confirm the price → click Proceed to Checkout before the timer runs out.

---

### PAGE 4 — Checkout (Stripe-Hosted, `/checkout` → Stripe Page)
**Who sees it:** Logged-in users who click "Proceed to Checkout"

This is NOT a page built by the platform. The user is **redirected to Stripe's secure, hosted payment page**. Stripe handles:
- Credit/debit card entry
- Card validation and fraud checks
- 3D Secure authentication if required
- Payment processing

**What a user does here:** Enter card details on Stripe's page → click Pay.

**Two outcomes after payment:**
1. ✅ **Payment succeeds** → Stripe sends a webhook to the platform → user is redirected to the Confirmation page
2. ❌ **Payment fails** → User is redirected back to the cart page with an error → the booking returns to "Available" and seats are released

---

### PAGE 5 — Booking Confirmation (`/bookings/[id]/confirmation`)
**Who sees it:** Users whose payment has been confirmed

This is the success page — proof that the booking is complete and payment was received.

**What's on this page:**
- **Success Banner** — "🎉 You're going! Booking confirmed."
- **Booking Reference Number** — A unique booking ID for support queries
- **Event Summary** — Event name, date, venue, number of tickets
- **Ticket Cards** (one per ticket) — Each ticket card shows:
  - Seat/ticket details
  - **QR Code** (may show a loading spinner briefly — QR codes are generated asynchronously after payment, so the page polls until they appear)
  - Download / Save to Wallet button
- **"View My Bookings" link** → goes to the My Bookings page

**What a user does here:** Save/screenshot the QR code → optionally download tickets → share with friends.

---

### PAGE 6 — My Bookings (`/my-bookings`)
**Who sees it:** Logged-in users

The user's personal dashboard for all their ticket purchases, past and future.

**What's on this page:**
- **Booking List** — All bookings, filterable by status (Upcoming / Past / Cancelled)
- **Each Booking Row** shows:
  - Event name and date
  - Number of tickets
  - Total paid
  - Booking status badge (`CONFIRMED`, `ATTENDED`, `CANCELLED`, `REFUND_REQUESTED`, etc.)
  - Action buttons based on status:
    - `CONFIRMED` → "View Tickets" + "Request Refund" (if eligible)
    - `REFUND_REQUESTED` → "Refund Pending" (disabled)
    - `REFUND_DENIED` → "Refund Denied — [reason]"
    - `ATTENDED` → "View Tickets" (read-only)
    - `CANCELLED` → "Event Cancelled — Refund Issued"
- **Refund Request Modal** — When clicking "Request Refund":
  - Shows the refund eligibility (full refund / 50% / not eligible)
  - Confirmation button

**What a user does here:** Review their booking history → re-download QR codes → request refunds → track refund status.

---

### PAGE 7 — Organizer / Admin Dashboard (`/admin`)
**Who sees it:** Users with the Organizer or Admin role only

The management interface for event organizers. Regular users cannot access this page.

**What's on this page:**
- **My Events List** — All events created by this organizer, with status (Draft, Published, Sales Open, Completed)
- **Create Event Button** → Opens a form/wizard:
  - Event title, description, category, venue
  - Date and time
  - Ticket tiers (name, price, quantity per tier)
  - Enable/disable: Early Bird pricing, Dynamic Pricing, Waitlist
- **Event Management Panel** (when an event is selected):
  - Edit event details
  - View real-time ticket sales and revenue
  - View booking list for the event
  - **Check-In Mode** — A QR code scanner interface:
    - Organizer scans attendee's QR code at the event door
    - System validates the code → marks booking as `ATTENDED` → shows ✅ or ❌
  - Cancel Event button (triggers automatic refunds for all confirmed bookings)

**What an organizer does here:** Create events → manage them → use check-in mode on event day → view sales analytics.

---

## COMPLETE CLIENT WORKFLOW — From First Visit to Attended Event

---

### CHAPTER 1 — Discovery (Guest, no account needed)

```
1. User visits the platform homepage (/)
2. Sees the event grid — no login required to browse
3. Searches "Jazz Festival" in the search bar
4. Filters: Category = Music, Date = This month
5. Sees 3 matching event cards
6. Clicks on "New York Jazz Weekend"
7. Lands on the Event Detail page (/events/42)
8. Reads the description, lineup, venue details
9. Sees two ticket tiers:
   - General Admission: $49 (120 seats left)
   - VIP: $149 (8 seats left — "Limited!")
10. Decides they want 2x General Admission tickets = $98 total
11. Clicks "Reserve Now" → prompted to log in
```

---

### CHAPTER 2 — Registration & Login (One-time setup)

```
12. Clicks "Sign Up" → fills in name, email, password
13. Account created → automatically logged in
14. Returned to the Event Detail page they were viewing
    (the system remembers where they came from)
```

---

### CHAPTER 3 — Reservation (The 5-Minute Window Begins)

```
15. User is now logged in on /events/42
16. Selects: 2 tickets, General Admission ($49 each)
17. Clicks "Reserve Now"
18. SYSTEM: In the background (invisible to the user):
    - Acquires a Redis lock for this user+tier combo
    - Checks that 2+ seats are available (Redis fast check)
    - Decrements inventory from 120 → 118 (atomic Lua script)
    - Creates a Booking record (status: RESERVED)
    - Creates 2 Ticket records
    - Sets a 5-minute expiry timer
    - Releases the Redis lock
19. User is redirected to the Cart page (/cart)
20. Cart page shows:
    - ⏱ "Your seats are held for 4:59"
    - Event: New York Jazz Weekend
    - 2x General Admission @ $49 = $98
    - No early bird discount (event < 30 days away)
    - No group discount (< 5 tickets)
    - Total: $98.00
```

---

### CHAPTER 4 — Checkout & Payment

```
21. User clicks "Proceed to Checkout"
22. SYSTEM: Creates a Stripe Checkout Session
    - Booking moves to status: PAYMENT_PENDING
    - Seat hold timer continues counting down
23. User is redirected to Stripe's secure payment page
24. User sees: "New York Jazz Weekend — 2 tickets — $98"
25. User enters card: 4242 4242 4242 4242 (test card)
26. Clicks "Pay $98.00"
27. Stripe processes the payment (1-2 seconds)
28. Stripe sends a webhook to the platform:
    "Payment for booking #1001 was successful"
```

---

### CHAPTER 5 — Confirmation (Behind the Scenes → Then the Good Stuff)

```
BEHIND THE SCENES (user sees only the confirmation page):
29. Stripe webhook arrives at the platform
30. System verifies Stripe's signature (security check)
31. System checks: "Have I processed this webhook before?" → No
32. System records the Stripe event ID (idempotency guard)
33. Booking status changes: PAYMENT_PENDING → CONFIRMED
34. Payment record created (amount=$98, status=PAID)
35. System publishes to RabbitMQ:
    Message 1: "Send confirmation email to user@email.com"
    Message 2: "Generate QR codes for booking #1001"
36. Database transaction commits
37. System returns HTTP 200 to Stripe (ONLY now, after DB commit)

ASYNC (happening in parallel):
38. Email notification listener:
    Receives Message 1 → sends confirmation email to user
39. QR code generation listener:
    Receives Message 2 → generates 2 QR codes (one per ticket)
    Saves QR codes to the database

WHAT THE USER SEES:
40. Stripe redirects the user to /bookings/1001/confirmation
41. Page loads: "🎉 You're going! Booking Confirmed"
42. Shows booking reference: #1001
43. Ticket cards area shows a loading spinner briefly
44. After 2-3 seconds, QR codes appear on each ticket card
45. User screenshots / downloads their QR codes
46. User also receives a confirmation email
```

---

### CHAPTER 6 — Event Day / Check-In

```
ON THE DAY OF THE EVENT:
47. User arrives at the venue
48. Opens the confirmation page on their phone
    OR opens the email with the QR code
49. Shows QR code to the event staff (organizer)

ON THE ORGANIZER'S DEVICE:
50. Organizer is on the /admin page in "Check-In Mode"
51. Organizer scans the user's QR code
52. SYSTEM: 
    - Validates the QR code belongs to a CONFIRMED booking
    - Verifies the organizer owns this event
    - Changes booking status: CONFIRMED → ATTENDED
53. Organizer's screen shows: ✅ VALID — 2 tickets, John Smith
54. User walks in
```

---

### CHAPTER 7 — Requesting a Refund (If Plans Change)

```
SCENARIO: User bought tickets but can no longer attend.
They do this 10 days before the event.

55. User goes to /my-bookings
56. Finds the "New York Jazz Weekend" booking (CONFIRMED)
57. Clicks "Request Refund"
58. Modal shows: "Event is 10 days away — Full refund eligible"
59. User confirms
60. SYSTEM:
    - Booking status: CONFIRMED → REFUND_REQUESTED
    - RefundService checks: 10 days away ≥ 7 days = FULL refund
    - Stripe refund issued: $98 to the user's card
    - Seats released back to inventory (120 again)
    - Booking status: REFUND_REQUESTED → REFUND_APPROVED
61. User receives refund confirmation email
62. My Bookings page shows booking as "Refund Approved"
63. Money returns to their card in 5-10 business days (Stripe standard)

SCENARIO B: User requests refund 2 days before the event:
- RefundService checks: 2 days < 3 days = DENIED
- Booking status: REFUND_REQUESTED → REFUND_DENIED
- User receives email explaining the refund policy
- My Bookings page shows: "Refund Denied — Event starts in 2 days. 
  Refund requests require at least 3 days' notice."
```

---

### CHAPTER 8 — Event Cancellation by Organizer

```
SCENARIO: The organizer has to cancel the entire event.

64. Organizer goes to /admin → My Events
65. Opens "New York Jazz Weekend" event management panel
66. Clicks "Cancel Event"
67. Confirms the cancellation

SYSTEM (for every confirmed booking, automatically):
68. Finds all CONFIRMED bookings for this event (e.g., 50 bookings)
69. For each confirmed booking:
    - Booking status → CANCELLED
    - Full Stripe refund issued automatically
    - Notification email sent: "New York Jazz Weekend has been cancelled.
      Full refund of $X has been issued to your card."
70. For each RESERVED booking (people mid-checkout):
    - Booking cancelled
    - Seats released
71. Event status → ARCHIVED

WHAT THE USER SEES:
72. User received a cancellation email
73. Goes to My Bookings → booking shows "Event Cancelled"
74. Shows: "Full refund of $98 issued — 5-10 business days"
```

---

## SUMMARY — The 4 States Every User Cares About

| Booking Status | What It Means for the User | Next Possible Action |
|---------------|---------------------------|---------------------|
| **RESERVED** | Seats held for you for 5 minutes | Pay now, or lose your seats |
| **CONFIRMED** | Payment received, tickets valid | Download QR code, request refund |
| **ATTENDED** | You checked in — event complete | Nothing, it's done ✅ |
| **CANCELLED** | Event cancelled or refund approved | Wait for refund on your card |

---

## THE PRICING LAYERS — How the Final Price Is Calculated

When a user selects tickets, the price shown goes through up to 3 adjustments:

```
Base Tier Price (set by organizer)
         │
         ├─ Early Bird? (buying 30+ days in advance)
         │    → -50% discount applied
         │
         ├─ Group Discount? (buying 5+ tickets)
         │    → -10% discount applied
         │
         └─ Dynamic Surge? (event is 80%+ sold out)
              → +25% increase applied

Final Price = (Base Price × applicable discounts/surges)
```

**Example:** $100 base tier, event is 85% sold out, user buys 6 tickets:
- Group discount: -10% → $90 per ticket
- Dynamic surge: +25% → $112.50 per ticket
- Total for 6: $675

The price shown on the Event Detail page and Cart page is always the final calculated price — no surprises at checkout.

---

## WHAT THE USER NEVER SEES (But Depends On)

These happen invisibly and are what make the system reliable:

| Invisible Feature | Why It Matters to the User |
|------------------|-----------------------------|
| **5-minute race protection** (Redis Lua guard) | If you and another user both try to buy the last seat at the same second, only ONE of you gets it — never both |
| **Stripe webhook reliability** | Your booking is only confirmed after your payment is definitely in the system — not just after the browser redirect |
| **QR code async generation** | You don't wait for your QR to be generated before seeing the confirmation — it appears within seconds automatically |
| **Expiry job** (runs every 30 seconds) | Abandoned carts are cleaned up automatically — if someone reserves tickets and disappears, those seats become available again |
| **Correlation ID tracing** | If something goes wrong and you contact support, they can trace your exact request through every system log |
| **Organizer-only check-in guard** | Only the event's own organizer can mark YOUR ticket as attended — another organizer cannot accidentally check you in to the wrong event |
